{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478745","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478745"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:15:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:15:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18805"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18805","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18805"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.23,0.2,0.07,0.47]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11538"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115470"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11538","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11538"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18805"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97473"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"183"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3406"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27160"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39091"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48385"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115470","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115470"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 12-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a two-week history of worsening fatigue, light-headedness when standing, and intense cravings for salty foods. His parent notes he has lost 3 kg over the past month and appears to be drinking more water than usual. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears lethargic. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 85/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is notable darkening of his skin, particularly prominent in the palmar creases and inside his mouth. His capillary blood glucose is 3.2 mmol/L (3.9-5.5).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Plasma renin activity","Short synacthen test","Serum aldosterone","21-hydroxylase antibodies","Morning cortisol and ACTH"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case demonstrates the hallmark features of primary adrenal insufficiency, with the combination of constitutional symptoms, postural symptoms, salt cravings, and characteristic hyperpigmentation. The presence of hypotension and borderline hypoglycaemia suggests significant glucocorticoid deficiency requiring urgent assessment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMorning cortisol and ACTH\u003C/strong\u003E levels are the essential first-line investigations. Cortisol levels normally peak in the early morning (around 8 am) due to the circadian rhythm, so a low morning cortisol is particularly significant and diagnostic. When paired with an elevated ACTH, this combination provides strong evidence for primary adrenal insufficiency. The elevated ACTH reflects the pituitary\u0027s attempt to stimulate the failing adrenal glands. These tests should ideally be collected before starting steroid therapy, as exogenous steroids will interfere with the interpretation of results. While acute adrenal crisis requires immediate treatment with hydrocortisone, in stable patients like this one, obtaining diagnostic samples first allows for definitive diagnosis before committing to lifelong steroid replacement therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eshort synacthen test\u003C/strong\u003E provides definitive confirmation of adrenal insufficiency by demonstrating an inadequate cortisol response to synthetic ACTH. However, this dynamic test takes several hours to complete and should not delay urgent treatment in a clinically unstable patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlasma renin activity\u003C/strong\u003E will typically be elevated in primary adrenal insufficiency due to mineralocorticoid deficiency. However, this is a secondary investigation that helps characterise the extent of hormone deficiency after the initial diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum aldosterone\u003C/strong\u003E measurement can help distinguish between primary and secondary adrenal insufficiency, as it is typically low in primary disease. However, this distinction is less urgent than establishing the basic diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E21-hydroxylase antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E can identify autoimmune adrenalitis, the most frequent cause of primary adrenal insufficiency in children. However, determining the specific aetiology is less urgent than confirming the diagnosis and initiating appropriate therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe priority in managing suspected adrenal insufficiency is to prevent or treat adrenal crisis. In severely unwell patients, empiric treatment with hydrocortisone and intravenous fluids should be initiated promptly, even before confirmatory test results are available. However, in stable patients presenting with chronic symptoms, obtaining diagnostic tests before starting steroids is preferable, as long-term steroid replacement therapy has significant implications and should be based on a confirmed diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Primary adrenal insufficiency classically presents with fatigue, orthostatic hypotension, hyperpigmentation, and salt craving.","Morning cortisol with paired ACTH is the essential first-line investigation, as low morning cortisol (when levels should peak) with elevated ACTH confirms primary adrenal insufficiency.","While acute adrenal crisis requires immediate treatment, long-term steroid therapy should ideally be commenced only after diagnostic confirmation."],"references":["Nistic\u00f2 D, Bossini B, Benvenuto S, Pellegrin MC, Tornese G. Pediatric Adrenal Insufficiency: Challenges and Solutions. Ther Clin Risk Manag. 2022 Jan 11;18:47-60. doi: 10.2147/TCRM.S294065. PMID: 35046659; PMCID: PMC8761033."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97473"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18805"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97473","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97473"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T20:57:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-24T14:49:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11538"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115470"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attr